The detailed description of the young bullock furnishes the ode with a quiet idyllic ending similar to that in 3, 5, 53—56. At the same time it emphasizes the contrast between the wealthy An- tonius, who must sacrifice twenty head of cattle off hand, and the simple Horace who loves to linger on the charms of his single victim.
